<P>It is not always our faults that ruin us, but the manner of our conduct after we have com|mitted them. An humble acknowledgment of our faults di&s;arms re&s;entment, and &s;tops the vio|lence of anger. Women that have had the mis|fortune to deviate from their duty&punc; to break through decorum, to part with their virtue and mode&s;ty, own &s;o much regard to cu&s;tom, and ought to have &s;uch a &s;en&s;e of their breach of <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> city, as to appear with a mortified air; it is a
